<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Form in HTML</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Form in HTML</h1>
    <li>
      An HTML form is used to collect user input. The user input is most often
      sent to a server for processing.
    </li>
    <li>
      An HTML form is a section of a document which contains controls such as
      text fields, password fields, checkboxes, radio buttons, submit button,
      menus etc.
    </li>
    <br />
    <h2>HTML Form Elements</h2>
    <h3>&lt;Form&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>
      The HTML &lt;form&gt; element is used to create an HTML form for user
      input.
    </li>
    <li>
      The &lt;form&gt; element is a container for different types of input
      elements, such as: text fields, checkboxes, radio buttons, submit buttons,
      etc.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Input&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>One of the most used form elements is the &lt;Input&gt; element.</li>
    <li>
      The &lt;Input&gt; element can be displayed in several ways, depending on
      the <b>type</b> attribute.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Label&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>
      The &lt;Label&gt; element defines a label for several form elements.
    </li>
    <li>
      The &lt;label&gt; tag is used to specify a label for an &lt;input&gt;
      element of a form. It adds a label to a form control such as text, email,
      password, textarea etc. It toggles the control when a user clicks on a
      text within the &lt;label&gt; element.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Select&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>The &lt;select&gt; element defines a drop-down list:</li>
    <li>The &lt;option&gt; element defines an option that can be selected.</li>
    <p>By default, the first item in the drop-down list is selected.</p>

    <h3>&lt;Textarea&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>The &lt;Textarea&gt; element defines a multi-line input field.</li>
    <li>
      The <b>Rows</b> attribute specifies the visible number of lines in a text
      area.
    </li>
    <li>
      The <b>Cols</b> attribute specifies the visible width of a text area.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Fieldset&gt; And &lt;Legent&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>
      The &lt;Fieldset&gt; element is used to group related data in a form.
    </li>
    <li>
      The &lt;Legent&gt; element defines a caption for the &lt;Fieldset&gt;
      element.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Datalist&gt;</h3>
    <li>
      The &lt;Datalist&gt; element specifies a list of pre-defined options for
      an &lt;input&gt; element.
    </li>
    <li>
      Users will see a drop-down list of the pre-defined options as they input
      data.
    </li>
    <li>
      The list attribute of the &lt;input&gt; element, must refer to the id
      attribute of the &lt;datalist&gt; element.
    </li>

    <h3>&lt;Button&gt; Element</h3>
    <li>The &lt;Button&gt; element defines a clickable button.</li>
    <hr />

    <h2>HTML Form Attributes</h2>

    <h3>Action Attribute</h3>
    <li>
      The input formaction attribute specifies the URL of the file that will
      process the input when the form is submitted
    </li>
    <p>
      <b>Note:</b> This attribute overrides the action attribute of the
      &lt;form&gt; element.
    </p>
    <li>
      The formaction attribute works with the following input types: submit and
      image.
    </li>
    <br />
    <h3>Enctype Attribute</h3>
    <li>
      The input Enctype attribute specifies how the form-data should be
      encoded when submitted (only for forms with method="post").
    </li>
  </body>
</html>
